:''For the Biblical event itself, see [[Crossing the Red Sea]].'' {{Infobox artwork | image_file = The Crossing fo The Red Sea.jpg | painting_alignment = right | image_size = 300px | title = The Crossing of the Red Sea | alt = | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | artist = [[Nicolas Poussin]] | year = 1633-1634 | height_metric = 155.6 | width_metric = 215.3 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | city = [[Melbourne]] | museum = [[National Gallery of Victoria]] | coordinates = | owner = }} '''''The Crossing of the Red Sea''''' is a painting by [[Nicolas Poussin]], produced between 1633 and 1634. It depicts the [[Crossing the Red Sea|crossing of the Red Sea]] by the Israelites, from chapter 14 of the [[book of Exodus]]. It was made as part of a pair of paintings (the other being ''[[The Adoration of the Golden Calf]]'') commissioned by Amadeo dal Pozzo, Marchese di Voghera of Turin, a cousin to [[Cassiano dal Pozzo]], Poussin's main sponsor in Rome. By 1685 the pair had passed to the Chevalier de Lorraine and in 1710 they were bought by Benigne de Ragois de Bretonvillers.
In 1741 the pair was bought from Samuel by [[Jacob Bouverie, 1st Viscount Folkestone|Sir Jacob Bouverie]], whose son [[William Bouverie, 1st Earl of Radnor|William]] became the first [[Earl of Radnor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artfund.org/artwork/1532/the-adoration-of-the-golden-calf |title=The Adoration of the Golden Calf |publisher=Art Fund |date= |accessdate=2012-11-09}}</ref> The Earls of Radnor owned the pair from then until 1945, when it was split for the first time and ''The Adoration of the Golden Calf'' was sold to the [[National Gallery]] in London. ''The Crossing of the Red Sea'' was acquired by [[Kenneth Clark]] for the [[National Gallery of Victoria]] in 1948<ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:56Gk4l8Y5aQJ:arthistoriography.files.wordpress.com/2011/05/anderson-on-burke.pdf+%22Crossing+of+the+Red+Sea%22+felton+1945&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESj9-tN92cMt1IYQFw8l5oUVNfaOoLdSD9mCkJkrkrIXqRzZ__hH5otEHoUOSefvNu43wXBW7rlQViazQ6thM0z1ttSSpXPdBQck_SEEsv5C4gU5KtP_TVPj_-n_qxuPfvAIL8EK&sig=AHIEtbQAwvv9Z1hJ9gGYWhalpNmp2ZtV6w Poussin Paintings]</ref><ref>[http://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/explore/ngv-collection/search?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHAlM0ElMkYlMkZ3d3cubmd2LnZpYy5nb3YuYXUlMkZjb2xhcHAlMkZwdWIlMkZhcnR3b3JrcyUyRjQyNzElMkZkZXRhaWxzJmFsbD0x NGV catalogue entry]</ref> using money from the [[Alfred Felton#Felton Bequest|Felton Bequest]], a fund originally left to the gallery in 1904 by the industrialist [[Alfred Felton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/01/11/1073769451690.html |title=The bequest of a century |publisher=www.theage.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-11-09}}</ref> In 2011 it underwent a major conservation project.<ref>[https://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/essay/the-poussin-project/ NGV conservation project on the painting]</ref>
